inistrators to control prostitution and sex workers. Bridging the gap between theory and policy, emphasizing the multilevel nature of prostitution policy, while also highlighting more effective policies on prostitution, migration and labour exploitation, this unique book fills a gap in the literature on this contentious and important social issue.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Prostitution & Sex Trade.2bisacsh1 aAltink, Sietske, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aAmesberger, Helga, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311119663340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447324263zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447324263/original  a978-3-11-119663-3 Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA